The correct answer is:

B) Double

Explanation:

  • Integer: Can store whole numbers only (no decimals), range: -32,768 to 32,767.
  • Byte: Stores only positive whole numbers from 0 to 255.
  • Long: Stores larger whole numbers (no decimals), range: -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647.
  • Double: Can store decimal or fractional numbers, with a very wide range and high precision.

✅ Double is the most suitable for storing decimal or fractional values in VBA.

The correct answer is:

A) Slicers allow multiple selections across different categories, while Timelines provide a range-based filter for dates.

✅ Explanation:

  • Slicers:

    • Are visual filter controls for categorical fields (e.g., Region, Product, Department).
    • Allow multiple selections across categories.
    • Can be used on non-date fields.

  • Timelines:

    • Are specialized slicers for date fields only.
    • Allow filtering by a range of dates (e.g., by years, quarters, months, or days).
    • Designed to visualize and filter time-based data more effectively than regular slicers.

❌ Why Other Options Are Incorrect:

  • B: Only Timelines support range-based filtering; slicers do not.
  • C: This reverses the actual functionality of slicers and timelines.
  • D: Both slicers and timelines allow multiple selections or ranges, not just single selections.

So, Option A accurately captures the core difference.

The correct answer is:

D) Both A and B

✅ Explanation:

If you have email addresses like name@example.com and want to split them into:

  • Username → name
  • Domain → example.com

You have two common options:

🅰️ Option A: 'Text to Columns' with Delimiter

  • Go to Data tab → Text to Columns
  • Choose Delimited
  • Use @ as the delimiter

✔ This splits the email into two columns: name and example.com

🅱️ Option B: Use a Formula

You can also use Excel formulas like:

  • Username:
    =LEFT(A1,FIND("@",A1)-1)

  • Domain:
    =RIGHT(A1,LEN(A1)-FIND("@",A1))

✔ This is more flexible if you want to preserve the original data or automate splitting.

🟢 Summary:

Both methods are valid and commonly used depending on the context, so the correct answer is → D) Both A and B.

The correct answer is:

A) WHEN

✅ Explanation:

In MySQL, the WHEN keyword is used within triggers to specify the conditions under which the trigger's handler (the code block) should execute.

For example, in a BEFORE INSERT trigger, you might write:

CREATE TRIGGER check_salary
BEFORE INSERT ON employees
FOR EACH ROW
WHEN (NEW.salary < 0)
BEGIN
   SIGNAL SQLSTATE '45000'
   SET MESSAGE_TEXT = 'Salary cannot be negative';
END;
CREATE TRIGGER check_salary
BEFORE INSERT ON employees
FOR EACH ROW
WHEN (NEW.salary < 0)
BEGIN
   SIGNAL SQLSTATE '45000'
   SET MESSAGE_TEXT = 'Salary cannot be negative';
END;

Here, WHEN (NEW.salary < 0) is the condition that controls whether the code inside the trigger executes.

❌ Why Other Options Are Incorrect:

  • B) IF: Used inside procedural code (e.g., IF...THEN...), not to define trigger activation.
  • C) ON: Used to specify the table the trigger is attached to (e.g., ON employees), not the condition.
  • D) UNDER: ❌ Not a valid keyword in MySQL for this purpose.

🟢 Summary:

To specify the condition under which a trigger’s handler should activate, use → A) WHEN.

The correct answer is:

C) INTERSECT

✅ Explanation:

  • INTERSECT is a set operator used in SQL to return only the common rows between two SELECT statements (i.e., the intersection of their result sets).

Example:

SELECT id FROM table1
INTERSECT
SELECT id FROM table2;
SELECT id FROM table1
INTERSECT
SELECT id FROM table2;

This will return only the ids that exist in both table1 and table2.

❗ Important Note for MySQL Users:

As of now, MySQL does not natively support the INTERSECT operator (unlike PostgreSQL or Oracle).

Instead, in MySQL, you can achieve the same result using an INNER JOIN or IN clause:

Alternative using INNER JOIN:

SELECT t1.id
FROM table1 t1
INNER JOIN table2 t2 ON t1.id = t2.id;
SELECT t1.id
FROM table1 t1
INNER JOIN table2 t2 ON t1.id = t2.id;

Alternative using IN:

SELECT id FROM table1
WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM table2);
SELECT id FROM table1
WHERE id IN (SELECT id FROM table2);

❌ Why Other Options Are Incorrect:

  • A) FIND: Not a valid SQL operator or keyword for this purpose.
  • B) COMMON: Not a recognized SQL keyword.
  • D) MATCH: Used in full-text search, not for comparing result sets.

🟢 Summary:

  • In SQL, the operator to find common rows is → C) INTERSECT.
  • In MySQL, use an INNER JOIN or IN clause instead, since INTERSECT is not supported directly.

The correct answer is:

A) UNION

✅ Explanation:

In MySQL, the **UNION** operator is used to combine the results of two SELECT statements and eliminate duplicate rows by default.

🔍 Details:

  • UNION:

    • Combines results from multiple SELECT statements.
    • Removes duplicates unless specified otherwise.

  • UNION ALL:

    • Combines all rows including duplicates.

Example:

SELECT city FROM customers
UNION
SELECT city FROM suppliers;
SELECT city FROM customers
UNION
SELECT city FROM suppliers;

✔ This returns a distinct list of cities from both tables.

❌ Why Other Options Are Incorrect:

  • B) UNION DISTINCT:
    ✅ Technically valid in some databases, but in MySQL it's redundant — UNION already implies DISTINCT.

  • C) INTERSECT:
    Not supported in MySQL natively. Used to get common rows, not to eliminate duplicates.

  • D) EXCEPT:
    Also not supported in MySQL. Used in other databases to return rows in one result set but not in another.

🟢 Summary:

To combine two SELECT results and eliminate duplicate rows in MySQL, use → A) UNION.

The correct answer is:

C) SAVEPOINT

✅ Explanation:

In MySQL, the **SAVEPOINT** command is used to:

  • Set a named point within a transaction.
  • Allow partial rollbacks to that point without affecting the entire transaction.

🔍 Syntax:

SAVEPOINT savepoint_name;
SAVEPOINT savepoint_name;

You can then ROLLBACK TO that point:

ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT savepoint_name;
ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT savepoint_name;

Or release it:

RELEASE SAVEPOINT savepoint_name;
RELEASE SAVEPOINT savepoint_name;

Example:

START TRANSACTION;

UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 500 WHERE id = 1;

SAVEPOINT before_credit;

UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 500 WHERE id = 2;

-- If something goes wrong, rollback only the credit:
ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT before_credit;

COMMIT;
START TRANSACTION;

UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 500 WHERE id = 1;

SAVEPOINT before_credit;

UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 500 WHERE id = 2;

-- If something goes wrong, rollback only the credit:
ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT before_credit;

COMMIT;

❌ Why Other Options Are Incorrect:

  • A) COMMIT: Ends and commits the whole transaction.
  • B) ROLLBACK: Rolls back the entire transaction (unless used with TO SAVEPOINT).
  • D) BEGIN TRANSACTION: Starts the transaction, doesn’t set a savepoint.

🟢 Summary:

To set a specific point within a transaction for possible partial rollback, use → C) SAVEPOINT.

A) Copy the data, right-click on the destination, and select Paste Special > Transpose

✅ Explanation:

To transpose data (i.e., switch rows to columns and vice versa) using Paste Special in Excel:

📌 Steps:

  1. Select the data you want to transpose.
  2. Copy it (Ctrl + C or right-click → Copy).
  3. Right-click on the cell where you want the transposed data to begin.
  4. Select Paste Special.
  5. Check the Transpose checkbox.

✔ This pastes the data with rows and columns switched.

❌ Why Other Options Are Incorrect:

  • C) Drag and drop with Shift: ❌ This moves data but doesn't transpose it.
  • D) Use the TRANSPOSE function: ✅ Possible, but it's not using Paste Special — it’s a formula method.

🟢 Summary:

To transpose using Paste Special, always copy the data, then choose →
A) Copy the data, right-click on the destination, and select Paste Special > Transpose.

The correct answer is:

C) Dual-axis charts use separate axes, while combined-axis charts merge measures into a single axis.

✅ Explanation:

In Tableau, both dual-axis and combined-axis charts help display multiple measures in one view, but they differ in how the axes are handled:

🔹 Dual-Axis Charts:

  • Two separate axes (left and right) for two different measures.
  • Useful when measures have different scales (e.g., Revenue vs. Profit Margin).
  • You can synchronize axes if needed.
  • Allows for different chart types (e.g., bar + line combo).

🧭 Example:

Left Y-Axis: Sales ($)
Right Y-Axis: Profit (%)
Left Y-Axis: Sales ($)
Right Y-Axis: Profit (%)

🔹 Combined-Axis Charts:

  • Single shared axis for multiple measures.
  • Used when the measures are on the same or similar scale.
  • All data points are plotted on the same axis, often as grouped bars or lines.

🧭 Example:

Y-Axis: Count
Series: Number of Orders and Number of Returns (both plotted together)
Y-Axis: Count
Series: Number of Orders and Number of Returns (both plotted together)

❌ Why Other Options Are Incorrect:

  • A) Partially true, but it doesn’t clearly define the key difference (separate vs. single axis).
  • B) Describes a secondary effect, not the structural difference.
  • D) Incorrect — they are definitely different chart types.

🟢 Summary:

  • Dual-Axis = Two separate axes
  • Combined-Axis = One shared axis
    → Correct answer: C) Dual-axis charts use separate axes, while combined-axis charts merge measures into a single axis.
